# Laturo Grammar System (Rochopelic Root System)

## Capitalization Rules (IMPORTANT)
1. First letter of sentence: ALWAYS capitalized
   Example: Mo estar bono. (I am well.)
   
2. Proper names (people, places): ALWAYS capitalized
   Example: Kiro, Maria, Laturo, Paris, Tokyo
   CULTURAL NOTE: Not capitalizing person's names or given names is viewed as DISRESPECTFUL
   This is considered an insult to the person and shows lack of respect
   WRONG (disrespectful): kiro, maria, john
   CORRECT (respectful): Kiro, Maria, John
   
3. Middle of words: NEVER capitalized
   WRONG: manČar, dečIdar, koČinar
   CORRECT: mančar, dečidar, kočinar
   
4. All other words: lowercase only
   Example: mo, to, estar, senar, bono, malo
   
5. Acronyms: Can be all caps or lowercase
   Example: DNA or dna, RNA or rna, USB or usb
   
6. Brand names and proper nouns: Capitalize as appropriate
   Example: Google, Firefox, Chrome, DuckDuckGo

## Word Order
Basic: Subject-Verb-Object (SVO)
Questions: Verb-Subject-Object (VSO) or use question particle "vo"

## Nouns

### Gender
Laturo has 3 genders:
- Masculine: -o ending (vimo = man)
- Feminine: -a ending (vima = woman)
- Neutral: -e ending (vime = person)

### Number
- Singular: base form
- Plural: add -r suffix (vimo → vimor = men)
- Collective: add -ná suffix (vimo → vimoná = mankind)

### Cases
1. Nominative (subject): base form
2. Accusative (direct object): add prefix "el-" or use particle "ela"
3. Genitive (possession): add suffix "-ko" or use particle "do"
4. Dative (indirect object): add suffix "-ti" or use particle "ti"
5. Locative (location): add suffix "-pe" or use particle "pe"

## Verbs

### Tenses
- Present: base + -á (tinará = speaks/is speaking)
- Past: base + -ó (tinaró = spoke)
- Future: base + -é (tinaré = will speak)
- Present Perfect: base + -ála (tinarála = has spoken)
- Past Perfect: base + -óla (tinaróla = had spoken)
- Future Perfect: base + -éla (tinaréla = will have spoken)

### Moods
- Indicative: standard conjugation
- Subjunctive: add prefix "si-" (sitinará = may speak)
- Imperative: base form + -i (tinari = speak!)
- Conditional: base + -ía (tinaría = would speak)

### Aspects
- Progressive: add "vim" before verb (vim tinará = is speaking)
- Habitual: add "kem" before verb (kem tinará = speaks regularly)
- Perfective: standard past tense
- Imperfective: past + "vim" (vim tinaró = was speaking)

### Voice
- Active: standard form
- Passive: add prefix "pa-" (patinará = is spoken)
- Reflexive: add prefix "re-" (retinará = speaks to oneself)

### Infinitive
Base form + -ar (tinár = to speak)

## Pronouns

### Personal Pronouns
- 1st singular: mo (I/me)
- 2nd singular: to (you)
- 3rd singular masc: lo (he/him)
- 3rd singular fem: la (she/her)
- 3rd singular neut: le (it/they singular)
- 1st plural: mor (we/us)
- 2nd plural: tor (you all)
- 3rd plural: lor (they/them)

### Possessive Pronouns
Add -ko suffix:
- moko (my/mine)
- toko (your/yours)
- loko (his)
- lako (her/hers)
- leko (its)
- morko (our/ours)
- torko (your/yours plural)
- lorko (their/theirs)

### Demonstrative Pronouns
- esta (this)
- ista (that)
- estar (these)
- istar (those)

### Interrogative Pronouns
- vo (what/which - general question marker)
- voka (who)
- voke (what)
- voki (when)
- voko (where)
- voku (why)
- voká (how)

## Adjectives

### Position
Before noun (descriptive) or after noun (restrictive)

### Agreement
Must agree with noun in gender and number:
- Masculine: -o (varmo = warm-masc)
- Feminine: -a (varma = warm-fem)
- Neutral: -e (varme = warm-neut)
- Plural: add -r (varmor, varmar, varmer)

### Comparison
- Positive: base form (varmo = warm)
- Comparative: add prefix "mi-" (mivarmo = warmer)
- Superlative: add prefix "ma-" (mavarmo = warmest)

## Adverbs
Form: adjective + -ná suffix
Example: varmo → varminá (warmly)

## Prepositions
- do (of, from, about)
- ti (to, for)
- pe (in, at, on)
- ko (with)
- so (without)
- de (by, through)
- vo (for questions)

## Conjunctions
- e (and)
- o (or)
- ma (but)
- ke (that, because)
- si (if)
- kando (when)
- mento (while)

## Particles
- vo (question marker - makes statement into question)
- na (negation - not)
- ja (affirmation - yes)
- ne (emphasis)
- li (politeness marker)

## Sentence Structure

### Declarative
Subject + Verb + Object
Example: Mo tinará laturo. (I speak Laturo.)

### Interrogative
Vo + Subject + Verb + Object?
OR: Verb + Subject + Object + vo?
Example: Vo mo tinará laturo? / Tinará mo laturo vo? (Do I speak Laturo?)

### Negative
Subject + na + Verb + Object
Example: Mo na tinará laturo. (I don't speak Laturo.)

### Imperative
Verb-imperative + (Object)
Example: Tinari laturo! (Speak Laturo!)

## Word Formation (Rochopelic Root System)

### Root Structure
Most roots are CVC or CVCV patterns:
- tin- (speak/language)
- var- (warm/heat)
- vim- (person/human)
- kel- (good/well)
- mar- (big/great)

### Derivation
- Noun from verb: verb root + -o/-a/-e
- Verb from noun: noun root + -ar
- Adjective from noun: noun root + gender ending
- Adverb from adjective: adjective + -ná

### Compounding
Root1 + Root2 = compound word
Example: tin (speak) + vim (person) = tinvim (speaker)


## Capitalization Examples

### Correct Usage:
Mo nomo senar Kiro.
(My name is Kiro.)
- "Mo" capitalized (start of sentence)
- "Kiro" capitalized (proper name)
- All other words lowercase

Maria vivar pe Paris.
(Maria lives in Paris.)
- "Maria" capitalized (person's name)
- "Paris" capitalized (place name)
- All other words lowercase

Laturo senar belo lingvo.
(Laturo is a beautiful language.)
- "Laturo" capitalized (language name/proper noun)
- All other words lowercase

### Incorrect Usage (DO NOT USE):
❌ mo nomo senar kiro. (missing capitals)
❌ Mo Nomo Senar Kiro. (too many capitals)
❌ Mo nomo senar KIro. (capital in middle of name)
❌ Mo manČar panelo. (capital in middle of word)
❌ Mo DečIdar irar. (capitals in middle of word)

### Proper Names Include:
- Personal names: Kiro, Maria, Juan, Sofia, Ahmed
- Place names: Paris, Tokyo, London, Roma, Beijing
- Country names: Franča, Hispano, Japono, Ameriko
- Language names: Laturo, Englišo, Español, Français
- Company names: Microsoft, Google, Amazon
- Brand names: Toyota, Samsung, Apple
- Book/movie titles: First word capitalized
- Days/months: Can be capitalized or lowercase (flexible)

### Regular Words (Always Lowercase):
- Pronouns: mo, to, lo, la, le, mor, tor, lor
- Verbs: estar, senar, avar, fačar, venar, irar
- Adjectives: bono, malo, belo, grando, peto
- Nouns (common): panelo, laktelo, domelo, arbelo
- Adverbs: rapido, lento, bono, malo
- Prepositions: pe, ti, do, ko, so
- Conjunctions: e, o, ma, ke, si

### Sentence Examples:
Salut! Mo nomo senar Kiro e mo vivar pe Tokyo.
(Hello! My name is Kiro and I live in Tokyo.)

Maria e Juan parlar Laturo bono.
(Maria and Juan speak Laturo well.)

Vo to volar irar ti Paris o London?
(Do you want to go to Paris or London?)

Moko amiko Ahmed labar pe Microsoft.
(My friend Ahmed works at Microsoft.)

## Special Cases:

### Titles and Honorifics:
- Can be capitalized: Doktoro Silva, Profesoro Martinez
- Or lowercase: doktoro silva, profesoro martinez
- Both acceptable, but be consistent

### Acronyms and Abbreviations:
- Technical terms: DNA, RNA, USB, HTTP, CPU
- Can also be: dna, rna, usb, http, cpu
- Both forms acceptable

### Emphasis:
- Do NOT use capitals for emphasis
- Use particles or word order instead
- WRONG: Mo AMAR esta!
- CORRECT: Mo amar esta multo! (I love this much!)

### Internet/Informal Writing:
- Follow same rules as formal writing
- No "all caps" for shouting
- No random capitalization for style
